</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=FAEBD7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/uagrul.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Agrul</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tavern Regular</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/17/01 12:08:28 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Points do mean something</span><hr size=1> I don't know if he does, but I do, Grimjaw.<br>
<br>
The only way to ensure that the Shadowknight would destroy the Druid under the current system is landing Darkness, which isn't a surefire bet.<br>
<br>
If Darkness doesn't land, it isn't that hard to kite the SK dead.<br>
<br>
To quote NoneCN (this is responding to None, not an addition to the above response):<br>
<br>
&quot;You are right. The level 60 warrior will still resist the same vs. a level 60 wizard. Poor example. Let's replace that with a level 50 warrior. The level 50 warrior should have a chance to resist, but he or she should not be immune. Nor should the level 40 warrior. The trend just screams to me &quot;Re-roll melee!&quot;&quot;<br>
<br>
He or she would be no more immune than a level 60 warrior with equal resists.<br>
<br>
A level 60 Warrior with 150 MR would resist 95% (guesstimate~) of the Roots cast about by a level 60 Wizard.<br>
<br>
Under the system I advocate (negate level effects on resists), a level 50 Warrior with 150 MR would also resist 95% of the Roots cast about by a level 60 Wizard.<br>
<br>
Under the system Verant advocates (this is making assumptions on their idea of &quot;slightly&quot;), a level 50 Warrior with 150 MR would resist a level 60 Wizard's Roots as if he were level 60, but had 125 MR (again, I don't know the exact formula, but the point is made regardless).<br>
<br>
&quot;Clearly, the resist changes were not everything Verant intended them to be. However, instead of further 'adjustment,' it would be better to focus energy on issues such as dispell, targetting (JBoots) and enchanter bugs (mezmerize) rather than experiment with a system that really was not that horrid.&quot;<br>
<br>
Instead of further adjustment of them, I think it would be better to fix them so as to make them identical to the proposed changes.  I would also like to see the various other bugs fixed, but I don't see any reason as to why Verant can't do both.<br>
<br>
&quot;Do I see the benefits in some changes to resists? Surely. Do I want levels to be the end all be all of PvP? Hardly. However, given the choice I would rather have the old system with bugs repaired than the 'new' system which was never tested, poorly programmed and implemented primarily to appease the level 10's who petition about dying every single night. If you could assure me that a few programmers would focus their efforts on PvP, great, change everything. If you tell me that these programmers are doing this during lunch hour before they get back to Luclin, no thanks. &quot;<br>
<br>
It's rather difficult to tell exactly how much effort Verant puts into things, as they don't tell us.<br>
<br>
However, given the choice between the current system, the old system w/ bugs fixed, and the proposed system w/ bugs fixed, I'd choose the 3rd.<br>
<br>
Verant hasn't lain out any choices for us, so I'm not sure how we know exactly how much effort they are willing to put into it.<br>
<br>
